## 1) The structure I’d trust with real money (and why)

Your direction (infra / domain / services / research separation, Parquet lakehouse + DuckDB querying, CCXT abstraction) is solid.

What I would *add* to make it “I’d actually risk money on this”:

* **Contracts-first core**: shared types, event schemas, and interfaces so everything plugs together without hidden coupling.
* **Data correctness gates**: gap/dup detection, timezone normalization, idempotent writes, and reproducible “as-of” queries (point-in-time).
* **Backtest realism**: fees, funding (if perps), slippage model, order constraints (min notional / step size), latency assumptions, and *no lookahead* enforced.
* **Order-state machine**: explicit lifecycle (created → submitted → partially filled → filled/cancelled/rejected) and reconciliation with exchange.
* **Observability + kill-switches**: structured logs, metrics, alerts, “stop trading now” switch, and automatic circuit breakers.

If those are in place, the architecture is the *kind* I’d be comfortable deploying — but I still wouldn’t go live until paper trading + invariants pass (more on that in the plan).

